This unusual site is located on a tiny peninsula just an hour outside of northern Taipei. Coming here, you'll find remarkable geological formations that resembles mushrooms, honeycombs, and even a queen's head. This one in the picture is also one of the popular formations resembling candlesticks. These sedimentary rocks are mostly the product of the constant waves crashing against the shore and erosion from the wind
.
.
Although these rocks weren't as big as I had imagined them to be, it was still quite a view. But I guess I wouldn't recommend people with trypophobia to come and see, especially the ones formed in the shape of honeycombs üòã
.
.

Kehilangan motivasi. Kapan kalian ngerasa paling unmotivated? Mungkin kalo lagi cari kerja (me, included üòÇ), atau udah dapet kerja tapi lagi bosen? Hayo. Kemarin-kemarin sih aku paling ngerasa ga termotivasi waktu lagi nulis skripsi ü§ì tapi untungnya bisa menyelesaikan dengan segenap tangis dan keringat hahahahaha. Pengen share aja beberapa hal yang bantu aku selama kehilangan motivasi. So, here goes:
.
.
1 Be around energetic people. Energetic people has a positive vibe that's contagious! Seeing them moving around all the time helps me push me off my ass and keep moving
.
.
2 Menyendiri. This may be counter-intuitive with the first one, but sometimes you gotta just do it. Especially kalo orang-orang di sekitar kamu has a negative energy, it would only drag you down even more and that's the worst. I do this one especially when I find myself not feeling very good, I would normally turn away or excuse myself, or go home and sleep. Sleep is the best therapy, aside from retail therapy üòÇ‚úå
.
.
3 Liburan alias piknik. Your soul needs to recharge! And it can even be a low budget trip, like to the grocery store, the gym, a book shop, or a museum. I'd count a walk to the kitchen as a trip üòã
.
.
4 Did I mention sleep? Hahaha
.
.
5 Most of the time I would just work through it. Even when it's not perfect or how I want it to be, at least I've got something done. When I'm all refreshed and motivated, I'm ready to get back to work üòä This works especially when you have a tight deadline, and basically that's how I ended up finishing my undergraduate thesis haha
.
.
What would you do when you're unmotivated?
.
.

caption.text:
You might think this picture is taken out of a post card or from the internet. No, this amateur piture was taken during our trip in Taroko. We started early in the morning to make sure we don't miss any of its beauty
.
.
We arrived at Xiangde Temple at around 2 p.m. after lunch. This photo was taken after a loong hike up thousands of stairs. Looking at this picture, I remember how we were panting while climbing the stairs üòÇ I  was so focused that I forgot to look back. But once I did, I saw this amazing view!
.
.
We get so caught up in life sometimes, that we forget to look back, take a break, and reflect on what we have, what we've achieved üòä Sometimes the grass may seem greener on the other side. But trust me, everyone has got their fair share on the goods and bads, that is life
.
.
The key is to be grateful. Stop, take a look behind you, look at how far you've got, the risks you took, the troubles you've overcome, the family you have, the friends who stayed, appreciate, then get back to work üëä
.
.

About HES (Disclaimer: untuk teman-teman yang tertarik untuk lanjut studi di Taiwan, terutama teman-teman sastra Cina)
Huayu Enrichment Scholarship adalah beasiswa yang diberikan Ministry of Education Taiwan. Di sini, siswa diberikan kesempatan untuk belajar bahasa Mandarin dan berlatih di tengah-tengah penutur aslinya, which I think is the best way to learn any language. Karena sebelumnya udah pernah belajar bahasa Mandarin, kalo lagi belajar di sini jadi suka bandingin sama dulu waktu belajar di Indonesia
.
.
Yang kita pelajari di sini adalah bahasa sehari-hari dan kebiasaan pemakaian kata dalam kalimat. Selain itu, pastinya kosa kata bertambah, jadi kalau bikin ÊñáÁ´† bisa lebih beragam. Untuk Ë™ûÊ≥ï atau grammar, sebagian besar sudah dipelajari di Indonesia
.

Taiwan memakai ÁπÅÈ´îÂ≠ó atau classic characters. Banyak kesalahan aku kalau menulis ada di karakter hanzi klasik ini, karena udh terbiasa belajar simplified, sampai di sini jadi kagok. Misalnya, ‰π∞ dan Ë≤∑, atau Êù• dan ‰æÜ.¬† The simplest things needs much attention. One of the things that I find interesting about hanzi is how each and every one of them isn't formed randomly, there's a reason or a story why it is written the way that it is

Perbedaan lainnya, peran dosen di Indonesia adalah sebagai fasilitator. Kalau ada masalah, mahasiswa 'dilepas' dan harus cari jawaban sendiri. Kalau salah, (kadang) dibenerin. I was first introduced to their songs a few months ago by a friend, it was called 'Someone that Loves You'. The title intrigued me, but I thought it would've been another mushy love song of either heartbreak or falling in love. Sound familliar? üòú But, no. I heard the song and then, BAM! It was everything but what I had imagined. I'm no music expert and I don't know how to describe it. You should listen to it for yourself.
.
.
This picture is one of the frames in the music video. I believe they took it somewhere downtown Tokyo? The lyric and video reminded me of modern love. How two people fall in love and had connections and few interactions. But then, either one of them will eventually disappear without having a bother to explain. Poof! Then I thought, don't take love too seriously. If it's meant to be, it will be. You know? üòú
.
.
I listened to some more of their songs and I fell more and more in love with them üòç Good Together, It Ain't Wrong Loving You, Coastal Love. These are just to list some of them that I've been listening to on repeat for weeks! .
.
Jadi, dengan tema 'Lagu Untukmu', I dedicate this song for y'all out there. Remember, you have someone that loves you! üíï

Honne, please please please, come to Indonesia. We need you üò´

(2/2) Your Waste
.
.
Setelah melihat betapa sadarnya warga di sini sama lingkungannya, aku jadi inget sama rumah sendiri. Di Indonesia sekarang banyak tokoh masyarakat dan lembaga, seperti @waste4change, yang mulai kampanye tentang kebersihan lingkungan. .
.
Pemerintah sendiri juga sudah berupaya untuk mengatasi masalah ini. Contohnya, seperti kota Depok, di mana sekarang udah ada sekitar 500 bank sampah yang tersebar di 11 kecamatan. Pada bulan Agustus 2015 kemarin, bank sampah di kecamatan Tapos bahkan bisa menghasilkan 14 juta rupiah loh! Selain itu, retribusi sampah juga udah dicabut, dengan harapan warga bisa memilah sampah langsung dari sumbernya.
.
.
Nah, ininih kesempatan buat tunjukin kita bisa bekerjasama baik dengan pemerintah. Yuk, pisahin sampah jadi sampah organik dan non-organik mulai dari sumbernya, artinya.. rumah sendiri! Hehe. Sampah organik nanti bisa diolah jadi pupuk atau dimasukin ke lubang biopori, sedangkan non-organik dikumpulin ke bank sampah, lumayan loh buat tambah-tambah üòú
.
.
Salah satu program unggulan kota Depok itu 'zero waste city'. How 'bout we make it a national program, as they do here? Ingat, kebersihan adalah sebagian dari iman üòäüòäüòä
.
.

(1/2) Your waste
.
.
Salah satu hal yang menarik perhatian aku waktu awal sampai di Taiwan adalah: suara ice cream truck yang lewat jam 2 siang. Hampir tiap hari dengernya, i thought to my self, "wow, they must reaaally love their ice cream here" üòÇ Beberapa minggu pas udah mulai settle down, baru tau itu bukan suara yang biasanya bikin anak kecil kegirangan. Ternyata itu adalah.. bunyi truk sampah. Lagunya apa? None other than the classical F√ºr Elise dan A Maiden's Prayer. Coba aja search di google: Taiwan rubbish truck
.
.
Menurut WSJ, tingkat limbah daur ulang Taiwan adalah 55% (U.S. with only 35%). Pada tahun 2013, limbah per orang dalam satu hari hanya 0,387kg. Sebuah penurunan yang cukup drastis dibangingkan tahun 1998, which was 1,143kg per orang. Sedangkan pada tahun yang sama, pendauran ulang limbah hanya sebesar 5.9%. 17 tahun kemudian jumlah itu meningkat jadi 55% üò± Truk sampah musikal ini lewat 5 hari dalam seminggu dan berhenti tiap beberapa meter ga jauh dari perumahan warga
.
.
Enough with the numbers
.
.
Setelah beberapa bulan tinggal di sini, aku perhatiin mereka bagi sampah jadi 3 bagian: general refuse, kitchen waste, dan recyclable. Buat general refuse mereka buang pakai plastic official dari pemerintah berwarna biru. Kalau kitchen waste, petugas udah sediain tong sampah yang terpisah. Sedangkan recyclable dipisah truknya (biasanya di belakang truk yang mainin lagu Beethoven itu)
.
.
Kalau liat kota-kota di sini sekarang, mungkin ga akan pernah nyangka dulu kota ini isinya tumpukan sampah yang baunya menggoda tikus. Sampai sekarang, honestly, belum pernah liat atau dengar tikus (ga nyari juga sih haha). Sekarang ngerti kenapa susah banget nemuin tempat sampah, ya Allah üò´ Yang bikin aku salut adalah warganya. Karena program ini udah diawali sejak tahun 1997, membuang sampah udah jadi communal and daily 
activity for everyone. Dalam benak mereka udah tertanam bahwa mereka cuma ada SATU cara buat buang sampah: the musical truck. Menurutku, ini contoh keberhasilan kerja sama pemerintah dan warga üëç
.
.
It is Taiwan's goal, as a whole, to be 'zero waste'
.
.

caption.text:
I see her almost everyday. She's the one who wipes the tables after us. Cleans the plates from any left over food. .
.
She's the one who occasionally have small talks with students over lunch time. "How was your day?" She would say. I wonder if anyone have ever asked hers. How was her day.
.
.
She comes early in the morning when I'm buying breakfast and stays until the night when I'm having dinner with friends. I wonder who she comes home to at night. How she gets home and cannot wait to relax her troubled mind and worn muscles.
.
.
I wonder where she would be if she wasn't here. If she had a choice. I wonder who puts the smile back on her face and gives her the energy to start another day.
.
.

caption.text:
What kind of people do I fall in love with? Well, not necessarily falling in love in the romantic kind of love. But to answer the question, I fall in love with passionate people üòç
.
.
Passion in anything, really. Photography, design, dance, singing, teaching, writing, cooking, flower arranging, doing someone's make up, drawing, knitting. You can be passionate about a certain kind of music, a book, or a movie. It really can be anything and shouldn't be that complicated.
.
.
I went to a friend's mom's house one time when she played us a song on the piano. As I was watching her, I saw  her being lost in her own delightful world. For a moment, I could see her rawness, almost being vulnerable. Ever saw a singer and how they cast a spell to the audience? Or a dancer seducing you with their intricate moves. The same goes to when you see someone speak of their passion. The glimmer in their eyes? It's magical.
.
.
Imagine being surrounded with passionate people. Not only you will get more knowledge from seeing things through their eyes, but it also motivates you to never stop exploring, learning, and growing. After all, you are the average of the people you surround yourself with.
.
.
I believe passion inspires possibility. It opens up a whole lot of possibilities of doing something different or in different ways. Passion is what I crave for, whether in finding and pursuing my own or seeing it through your eyes üëÄ And now you know how to cast a spell on me.
.
.
What's your passion? .
.

Salah satu peran OIC (Office of International Cooperation) NCCU adalah sebagai penghubung antara siswa international dengan siswa lokal. Hal ini pastinya jadi keuntungan bagi kedua belah pihak. Kita sebagai international students bisa memperkenalkan negara masing-masing. Sedangkan bagi mereka, dengan adanya Êñ∞ÂçóÂêëÊîøÁ≠ñ (New Southbound Policy), bisa mendorong siswa agar lebih banyak yang berkeinginan buat cari ilmu di luar, termasuk Indonesia. (Fyi, sekarang banyaaak banget pemuda Indonesia yang mencari ilmu di sini. Tapi ngga sebaliknya. Menurut MOE Taiwan, ada peningkatan signifikan jumlah siswa Taiwan yang pergi ke negara-negara Asia seperti Jepang, Korea, Thailand, Malaysia, dan Vietnam).
.
.
Bulan November lalu, aku dan beberapa teman dari NCCU-ISA berkesempatan untuk sharing tentang Indonesia ke teman-teman di Muzha Junior High School. Aku dan ka Kamielah memperkenalkan Indonesia secara keseluruhan, sedangkan ka Ardilla tentang kota asalnya, Padang.
.
.
I really can't describe the feeling when I saw their eyes light up when they found out that there are much more interesting things in Indonesia other than Pulau Dewata. And their innocence when asking: "Semua perempuan di Indonesia berpakaian (berhijab) kaya kalian ga sih?", or "Adat di pulau A dan pulau B sama ga?" üíï
.
.
Ketika ke luar dari zona nyaman, kita ngga cuma mempelajari suatu budaya baru dan belajar beradaptasi di dalamnya. Tapi kita juga belajar betapa kayanya tempat di mana kita berasal. Bahasa, budaya, adat, kearifan lokal, dan masih banyak lagi ‚ù§ Ada rasa kebanggaan tersendiri waktu memperkenalkan Indonesia ke mereka :") .
.
Oh, that longing feeling of coming home. Ini yang aku dapat selama beberapa jam yang dihabiskan bersama mereka.
.
.
@30haribercerita #30haribercerita #30hbc1705

This is probably going to be the story I tell every time people ask me about my first impression towards Taiwan. No, it's not this delicious looking bowl of Niuroumian. Although, it is the b e s t one in town. It suits my taste and is halal üòã Would totally recommend this place.
.
.
My first impression was of its people, their warmth and hospitality. One day, when @felliciamo and I still haven't found a place to stay, we were wandering around looking for any ads that says 'Áßü' (rent). We were starting to get desperate because this was the last day that we can sleep at the hostel we stayed in for the first couple of days.
.
.
When all of a sudden, we met a middle aged man in front of his garage who was playing Pokemon Go. We stopped and asked him whether he knows anyone who rents rooms.
.
.
At the time, we hadn't practiced using Chinese in a while, so he actually walked around the neighborhood with us and called the landlord for us. .
.
It was getting dark, and we were all starting to feel the grumble in our tummy. The man asked, 'You guys hungry?' We definitely were. And so he took us to a place which sells Niuroumian (it wasn't the place where I took this picture though üòÇ)
.
.
It turns out, the owner of the restaurant was a close friend of his. And dinner was on him! üò¢ I mean, it's the nicest thing a stranger could've done. .
.
Have you ever had this kind of experience? Or have you been on the other side where you're the one making a stranger's day a little easier? .
.
Let's start practicing these random acts of kindness and see how it doesn't only make their day better, but yours too. Spread the love üíï
.
.

caption.text:
Which one do you prefer? A melting pot or a salad bowl?
.
.
Diversity is what makes life interesting. I always think it's fascinating when people from different backgrounds come together. These are some of the people who came here with the same intention as me, and that is to improve our Mandarin (Belum, belum S2. That's a whole different story. Doakan ada rezeki ya üòÇ).
.
.
I've been in this kind of environment from the early days. But now that I'm wiser (?) than I was back then, I'm able to appreciate and take notice of some things I wasn't able to before. .
.
Like how a British classmate of mine has tea with milk e v e r y morning, and how you can still hear her cute British accent when she speaks Mandarin. Like how the Japanese always talk politely in a small voice. How it turns out that not every Russian loves vodka and not every Italian loves coffee and spaghetti. How the Mexicans enjoy their music loud and the Germans like their peace and quite. Or how you can see the difference between a big city boy and a laid back outskirts of town guy from Korea.
.
.
Diversity doesn't always have to be in an international community. It can be found in one country with people from the same cultural background. But still, even with the same background, you can spot the difference through their frame of thoughts, socio-economic class, religion, political beliefs, etc.
.
.
Being surrounded in diversity teaches you how to see things from a different point of view. It keeps life interesting. Despite all the differences, it challenges you to live peacefully side-by-side. So when we come across a disagreement, should we just agree to disagree?
.
.
So, a melting pot or a salad bowl?
.
.

caption.text:
Aku rindu suara adzan.
.
.
Pernah suatu hari, ibu tanya: "kapan terakhir kali ke masjid?" Jujur selama merantau, baru dua kali ke masjid. Kenapa? Karena jumlah dan jarak masjid dari tempat tinggal. Di seluruh Taiwan cuma ada tujuh masjid. Di Taipei ada dua, Taipei Grand Mosque di daerah Daan dan Taipei Cultural Mosque di daerah Zhongzheng. .
.
Aku baru dua kali ke Taipei Grand Mosque. Dari tempatku butuh sekitar satu jam lebih dan dua kali ganti kendaraan untuk sampai ke sana. Pertama kali ke sana, ngga sempat masuk karena lagi berhalangan. Kedua kalinya, aku solat maghrib berjamaah. .
.
Di sana ketemu beberapa TKW Indonesia yang ikut sholat bersama. Ada yang baru sampai di Taiwan beberapa jam sebelumnya, ada juga yang lagi bicara sama majikannya lewat telpon. "Iya, tunggu dulu, ini baru selesai. Nanti sekitar jam 7 sampai rumah," ujar salah satunya dalam bahasa Mandarin.
.
.
Selain itu, pernah juga ketemu dua perempuan asal Jakarta yang lagi istirahat di musholla dan baru sampai di Taipei waktu lagi main sama @auliafajrin73 di TMS. Mereka mau menghadiri pernikahan teman Taiwannya di Taizhong, dan lebih memilih untuk beristirahat di ruang kecil yg kira-kira cuma muat 5-6 jamaat dari pada memesan kamar hotel. .
.
Dari situ aku sadar. Ternyata di mana-mana rumah-Nya jadi tempat peristirahatan dan berkumpul yang paling aman dan nyaman. Ternyata kita bisa merasa sedikit seperti di rumah ketika berada di sana. Ketika sholat berjamaah di negeri yang penduduknya minoritas muslim.
.
.
Masih banyak hal-hal kecil yang kita anggap remeh.
.
.
Aku rindu suara adzan üòä
.
.

The beginning is always the most challenging, don't you think?

It's like writing a 15 page paper, not knowing how to even start putting the words together to form an effective sentence.

It's like going to school for the first time, and learning how to make life long friends.

It's like a first time parent, still learning how to properly hold their new born baby.

New begginings may be scary, for we are uncertain of what it may bring. But, just as I was waiting for 00:00 and the fireworks to set off last night, it didn't occur to me. Instead, I find myself being all giddy and excited for new years. Just like a child getting a new toy on their birthday. It's true I have no idea what the future holds. And it may scare me from time to time. But I know I wouldn't want to stand still in one place.

caption.text: From the early 6 a.m. coffee, to the frantic handling live report moments in the control room. The first time I operated the prompter, the feeling when I watch the news I wrote being read by the anchor, it was thrilling! It sure wasn't easy, and I made a lot of mistakes. But from them, I've learned a lot, and wish someday to be able to dig deeper and have the chance to absorb more knowledge from these intelligent people once more. I admire them so üòç They're just a few of a whole lot more. In the end, all I can say, is thank you.
